	h3
		b Axiom of extensionality
	p If two sets contain the same elements, they are equal.
	p $$\forall x \forall y[\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in y)\rightarrow x=y]$$
	p This introduces the equality relationship.
	p NOTE: WHY DOESN'T EQUALITY IMPLY SAME MEMBERSHIP? UNIDIRECTIONAL.
	h3
		b Properties of equality
	p
		b Reflexivity
	p The reflexive property is:
	p $$\forall x(x=x)$$
	p We can replace the quantifiers with just \(x\).
	p $$\forall x [\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in x)\rightarrow x=x]$$
	p We can show that the following is true:
	p $$\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in x)$$
	p Therefore \(x=x\)
	p
		b Symmetry
	p The symmetry property is:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[(x=y)\leftrightarrow (y=x)]$$
	p We know that the following are true:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in y)\rightarrow x=y]$$
	p $$\forall y \forall x[\forall z(z\in y \leftrightarrow z\in x)\rightarrow y=x]$$
	p The second can be reformed to:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in y)\rightarrow y=x]$$
	p So:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[\forall z(z\in x \leftrightarrow z\in y)\rightarrow (x=y\land y=x)]$$
	p
		b Transitivity
	p The transitive property is:
	p $$\forall x \forall y \forall z[(x=y \land y=z) \rightarrow x=z]$$
	p
		b Substitution for functions
	p The substitutive property for functions is:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[(x=y)\rightarrow (f(x)=f(y))]$$
	p
		b Substitution for formulae
	p The substitutive property for formulae is:
	p $$\forall x \forall y[((x=y)\land P(x))\rightarrow P(y)]$$
